The European Union has pledged to support the unity and development deal by President Uhuru Kenyatta and Opposition leader Raila Odinga. Raila made this announcement on Wednesday when he met ambassador Stefano-Antonio Dejak. "We discussed areas of common interest and he pledged their support for the Building Bridges Initiative in any capacity [as] called upon," he wrote on Twitter. UK Prime Minister Theresa May congratulated Uhuru and Raila on April 9, saying it was a great show of leadership. The message was delivered by High Commissioner Nic Hailey who met with Raila at Capitol Hill in Nairobi on that day. More on this: Support Uhuru-Raila handshake, UK PM Theresa May tells Kenyans The two leaders have appointed a team of 14 advisers to steer national dialogue on this initiative. They include Adams Oloo, Agnes Kavindu, Busia Senator Amos Wako, Florence Omose, Saeed Mwanguni, James Matundura, Major (rtd) John Seii, Bishop Lawi Imathiu, Maison Leshomo and Garissa Senator Mohamed Yusuf Haji. The others are Morompi ole Ronkai, Bishop Peter Njenga, Makueni Woman Representative Rose Museo and Zacchaeus Okoth. Related: Handshake with Uhuru ended ethnicity Click here for the latest political news  